18:33.300 --> 18:39.700
Indeed, it is the only social order that allows people to question even its own foundations.

18:39.700 --> 18:43.780
Liberalism has already survived three big crises, the first world war, the fascist challenge

18:43.780 --> 18:48.020
in the 1930s, and the communist challenge in the 1950s to 70s.

18:48.020 --> 18:51.940
If you think liberalism is in trouble now, just remember how much worse things were in

18:51.940 --> 18:54.700
1918, 1938, or 1968.

18:54.700 --> 18:59.420
See, so far this person seems to basically be on the money, but then we kinda get into

18:59.420 --> 19:01.760
some weird territory here.

19:01.760 --> 19:04.060
Liberalism is founded on the belief in human liberty.

19:04.060 --> 19:07.540
Unlike rats and monkeys, human beings are supposed to have free will.

19:07.540 --> 19:11.760
This is what makes human feelings and human choices the ultimate moral and political authority

19:11.760 --> 19:13.420
in the world.

19:13.420 --> 19:17.500
Liberalism tells us that the voter knows best, that the customer is always right, and that

19:17.500 --> 19:20.580
we should think for ourselves and follow our hearts.

19:20.620 --> 19:23.220
Unfortunately, free will isn't a scientific reality.

19:23.220 --> 19:27.340
It is a myth inherited from Christian theology.

19:27.340 --> 19:31.540
Theologians developed the idea of free will to explain why God is right to punish sinners

19:31.540 --> 19:35.460
for their bad choices and reward saints for their good choices.

19:35.460 --> 19:39.940
If our choices aren't made freely, why should God punish or reward us for them?

19:39.940 --> 19:44.100
According to theologians, it is reasonable for God to do so because our choices reflect

19:44.100 --> 19:48.500
the free will of our eternal souls, which are independent of all physical and biological

19:48.500 --> 19:49.500
constraints.

19:49.500 --> 19:54.260
This myth has little to do with what science now teaches us about homo sapiens and other

19:54.260 --> 19:55.260
animals.

19:55.260 --> 19:57.460
Humans certainly have a will, but it isn't free.

19:57.460 --> 19:59.820
You cannot decide what desires you have.

19:59.820 --> 20:05.140
You don't decide to be introverted or extroverted, easygoing or anxious, gay or straight.

20:05.140 --> 20:08.780
Humans make choices, but they are never independent choices.

20:08.780 --> 20:12.780
If every choice depends on a lot of biological, social, and personal conditions that you cannot

20:12.780 --> 20:17.860
determine for yourself, I can choose what to eat, whom to marry, and whom to vote for,

20:17.860 --> 20:21.820
but these choices are determined in part by my genes, my biochemistry, my gender, my

20:21.820 --> 20:24.340
family background, my national culture, etc.

20:24.340 --> 20:26.780
I didn't choose which genes or family to have.

20:26.780 --> 20:32.040
The problem with this point of view is that it's conflating circumstances with choices

20:32.040 --> 20:33.700
and they're not the same thing.

20:33.700 --> 20:35.140
What's a good example?

20:35.140 --> 20:36.420
Boogie is a good example.

20:36.420 --> 20:45.100
Boogie was like a 600 pound goliath of a man, like grotesquely fat, okay?

20:45.100 --> 20:51.060
But he has made the choice to make some lifestyle changes, and there was definitely some surgery

20:51.060 --> 20:54.960
along with that, but he made choices.

20:54.960 --> 21:00.100
In fact, the choice to get the surgery was a choice too, and as a result of those choices,

21:00.100 --> 21:01.100
he's losing weight.

21:01.100 --> 21:05.500
He's significantly thinner than he was before.

21:05.500 --> 21:10.900
Circumstances are not choices, and they can influence choices, but people always have

21:10.900 --> 21:15.260
the ability to choose beyond their circumstances.

21:15.260 --> 21:20.500
A fat person who has been fat their whole life, who chooses beyond their circumstances

21:20.500 --> 21:23.320
to become thin, that's free will.

21:23.320 --> 21:28.600
An alcoholic who has been drinking for 20 years, who makes the choice to stop, that's

21:28.600 --> 21:29.600
free will.

21:29.600 --> 21:33.660
It's not easy, no one's saying that it's easy, but the choice is still there.

21:33.660 --> 21:35.300
This is not an abstract theory.

21:35.300 --> 21:36.500
You can witness this easily.

21:36.500 --> 21:38.900
Just observe the next thought that pops up in your mind.

21:38.900 --> 21:40.040
Where did it come from?

21:40.040 --> 21:42.120
Did you freely choose to think it?

21:42.120 --> 21:43.120
Obviously not.

21:43.120 --> 21:46.960
If you carefully observe your own mind, you come to realize that you have little control

21:46.960 --> 21:50.880
of what's going on there, and that you are not choosing freely what to think, what to

21:50.880 --> 21:53.380
feel, and what to want.

21:53.380 --> 21:54.380
That's partially true.

21:54.380 --> 21:57.960
However, that does not disprove free will, does it?

21:57.960 --> 22:02.920
I mean, yeah, there's obviously some kind of unconscious part of your mind that you

22:02.920 --> 22:05.840
do not have any kind of free will over.

22:05.840 --> 22:09.280
You're going to get stray thoughts, you're going to get dreams, you're going to get all

22:09.280 --> 22:13.880
these situations, and yet you can still choose what you do with them.

22:13.880 --> 22:18.520
You can get some kind of thought in your mind, you can choose to ignore it, you can choose

22:18.520 --> 22:23.300
to act on it, you can choose to ruminate on it but not actually perform any action.

22:23.300 --> 22:25.640
You can do a lot of things.

22:25.640 --> 22:31.760
Just because there are some uncontrollable parts of yourself doesn't mean that you are,

22:31.760 --> 22:34.480
on the whole, uncontrollable.

